The long old Roman hasta, whence the name hastati, had long before Cato’s time been discarded for the pilum or short Javelin, which was thrown at the enemy from a dis- tance, before the troops closed and used the sword. —-— consilium: the repetition of consilium in a different sense from that which it had in the sentence before seems to us awkward; but many such repeti· tions are found in Cicero. Consilium corresponds to both ‘ counsel ’⁶ and ‘ council ’3 the senate was originally regium consilium, the king’s body of advisers. Here translate summum consilium ‘the supreme deliberative body ⁹. — senatum: ‘ assembly of elders ’. Cf. 56 sena· tores, id est senes. Senatus implies a lost verb send-re, to be or grow old, from the stem of which both send-tus and senei-tor are derived. This stem again implies a lost noun or adjective senus, old. The word senatus was collective, like comitatus, a body of companionS, excreans, a trained band etc.
